'''Jennifer Anne Garner''' (born April 17, 1972)<ref name=filmref>{{cite web | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/33/Jennifer-Garner.html| title= Jennifer Garner Biography (1972–)| publisher=FilmReference.com | accessdate= July 1, 2015}}</ref> is an American actress. Following a supporting role in ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' (2001), Garner gained recognition for her performance as [[CIA]] officer [[Sydney Bristow]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] spy-action thriller ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'', which aired from 2001 to 2006. For her work on the series, she won a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress - Television Series Drama|Golden Globe Award]] and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Screen Actors Guild Award]], and received four [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations.

While working on ''Alias'', Garner gained a [[Cameo appearance|cameo]] role in ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'' (2002), followed by a praised leading performance in the romantic comedy film ''[[13 Going on 30]]'' (2004). Garner has appeared in supporting as well as lead film roles, including the superhero films ''[[Daredevil (film)|Daredevil]]'' (2003) and ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'' (2005), the comedy-drama ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' (2007), and the fantasy-comedy ''[[The Invention of Lying]]'' (2009). In the 2010s, she appeared in the romantic-comedy ''[[Valentine's Day (2010 film)|Valentine's Day]]'' (2010), the fantasy comedy-drama ''[[The Odd Life of Timothy Green]]'' (2012), the biographic drama ''[[Dallas Buyers Club]]'' (2013), the comedy film ''[[Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day (film)|Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day]]'' (2014), the drama film ''[[Miracles from Heaven (film)|Miracles from Heaven]]'' (2016), and the romantic comedy-drama film ''[[Love, Simon]]'' (2018).

Garner works frequently as an activist for early childhood education and is a board member of [[Save the Children]]. She is also an advocate for anti-paparazzi campaigns among children of celebrities. Garner had a five-year relationship with [[Scott Foley]] from 1998 to 2003, during which they married. Garner married actor [[Ben Affleck]] in 2005; they separated in 2015 and divorced in 2018. Garner and Affleck have three children together.

== Early life==
Jennifer Garner was born on April 17, 1972, in [[Houston, Texas]], but moved to [[Charleston, West Virginia]] at the age of three. She is the second of three daughters.<ref name="telegraph1">{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Saban|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3590033/Fighting-fit.html |title=Fighting fit |publisher=Telegraph |date=February 16, 2003 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Her father, William John Garner, worked as a chemical engineer for [[Union Carbide]], and her mother, Patricia Ann (née English), was a homemaker and, later, an English teacher at a local college.<ref name="rollingstone1">{{cite web|last=Binelli |first=Mark |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/features/spy-girl-20020214 |title=Jennifer Garner: Spy Girl |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=February 14, 2002 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Connelly |first=Chris |url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a775/jennifer-garner-interview/ |title=The Zen of Jen (and Ben) |publisher=Marieclaire.com |date=September 11, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Garner has described herself as a typical middle child who sought to differentiate herself from her accomplished older sister.<ref name="telegraph2">{{cite web|first=Helena|last=de Bertodano |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/9954437/Jennifer-Garner-interview-Mrs-Ben-Affleck-on-juggling-fame-and-family.html |title=Jennifer Garner interview: Mrs Ben Affleck on juggling fame and family |publisher=Telegraph |date=April 1, 2013 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Pringle>{{cite news|last=Pringle|first=Gill|title=Jennifer Garner: Actress with the ex factor|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/jennifer-garner-actress-with-the-ex-factor-1679610.html|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=June 10, 2013 |date=May 6, 2009|location=London}}</ref> While Garner did not grow up in a politically active household,<ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a9200/princess-bride-19314/ |title=Princess Bride |publisher=Elle.com |date=December 12, 2006 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> her father was "very conservative" and her mother "quietly [[Red states and blue states|blue]]."<ref name="stern1">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/05/jennifer-garner-pregnant-talks-butter-and-ben-affleck-at-telluride.html|title=Jennifer Garner's Screwball Turn|first=Marlow|last=Stern |date=September 5, 2011|publisher=}}</ref> She attended a local [[United Methodist Church]] every Sunday and went to [[Vacation Bible School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/miracles-from-heavens-jennifer-garner-on-her-emotional-role-in-miracles-from-heaven-and-keeping-it-professional |title=Jennifer Garner on her latest emotional role and keeping it professional as a mom, on and offscreen &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> As teenagers, she and her sisters were not allowed to wear makeup, paint their nails, pierce their ears or dye their hair;<ref>{{cite news|last=Bianco|first=Robert|title=Sydney Bristow in the flesh|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/enter/tv/2002/2002-02-01-garner.htm|website=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=January 8, 2013|date=January 31, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Bobbi|last=Brown |url=https://www.yahoo.com/beauty/jennifer-garner-is-done-with-diets-108660786148.html |title=Jennifer Garner is Done with Diets & High-Maintenance Beauty |publisher=Yahoo.com |date=January 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> she has joked that her family's "take on the world" was "practically [[Amish]]."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/10/17/Treading-warily-around-social-media/stories/201410170008?pgpageversion=pgevoke |title=Jennifer Garner is treading warily around social media &#124; Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

Garner attended [[George Washington High School (Charleston, West Virginia)|George Washington High School]] in Charleston;<ref name="holidays">{{cite news|title=Garner happy to be home for holidays|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2003-12-26-garner-home_x.htm|website=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|accessdate=January 8, 2013|date=December 26, 2003}}</ref> she played saxophone in the marching band and was water girl for the football team.<ref name="telegraph1"/><ref name="rollingstone2002">Binelli, Mark (February 14, 2002). [https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/features/spy-girl-20020214 "Jennifer Garner: Spy Girl"]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref> While Garner was not a bad student, she did not get "straight As" and instead wanted to perform "in any kind of production."<ref name="stern1"/> She participated in musicals at the local community theater, the Charleston Light Opera Guild,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/20040416/features/jennifergarner.shtml |title=April 2004 &#124; blackfilm.com &#124; features &#124; interviews &#124;an interview with jennifer garner |publisher=blackfilm.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and took piano, singing and ballet lessons.<ref name="rollingstone2002"/><ref name="telegraph1"/> In 1990, Garner enrolled at [[Denison University]] in [[Granville, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coedmagazine.com/2007/08/02/co-ed-interview-with-jennifer-garner/ |title=CO-ED Interview with Jennifer Garner |publisher=[[COED (website)|COED]]|date=August 2, 2007 |accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> where she changed her major from chemistry to theater<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/oprahsbookclub/Books-That-Made-a-Difference-to-Jennifer-Garner What's on Jennifer Garner's Bookshelf?], Oprah.com</ref> and was a member of [[Pi Beta Phi]] sorority.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sprankles|first1=Julie|title=Jennifer Garner and 30 other celebrities in sororities|url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/1069871/jennifer-garner-and-other-celebrities-in-sororities|website=SheKnows|accessdate=July 2, 2017}}</ref> She spent the fall semester of 1993 studying at the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center#National Theater Institute|National Theater Institute]] at the [[The Eugene O'Neill Theater Center|Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]] in [[Waterford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BWW-Exclusive-NTI-Changed-My-Life-Jennifer-Garner-20150209 |title=BWW Exclusive: NTI Changed My Life – Jennifer Garner |publisher=Broadwayworld.com |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 1994 she graduated with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree in theater performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denison.edu/offices/publicaffairs/pressreleases/garner.html |title=Denison Graduate and 'Alias' Star Jennifer Garner To Speak at Provost Alumni Series Convocation – Denison University |publisher=Archive.is |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120731122533/http://www.denison.edu/offices/publicaffairs/pressreleases/garner.html |archivedate=July 31, 2012 |df=}}</ref>

== Acting career ==

===1994–2001: Career beginnings and ''Alias''===
As a college student, Garner did [[summer stock theatre|summer stock theater]]. In addition to performing, Garner helped to sell tickets, build sets, and clean the venues.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jennifer |last=Garner |url=http://teamcoco.com/video/jennifer-garner-die-hard-streaker |title=Jennifer Garner Was A Die-Hard Streaker @ |publisher=Teamcoco.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> She worked at the [[Timber Lake Playhouse]] in [[Mount Carroll, Illinois]] in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/tv/carolinian-likes-softer-side-as-psl-reporter/article_ec9553f5-5eb4-5c23-be56-30a8f8ebc52b.html |title=Carolinian likes 'softer side' as 'PSL' reporter &#124; TV News |publisher=qctimes.com |date=December 20, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> the Barn Theatre in [[Augusta, Michigan]] in 1993,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2014/10/jennifer_garner_streaked_clean.html |title=Jennifer Garner streaked, cleaned bathrooms well at The Barn Theatre, actress tells Conan |publisher=MLive.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and the [[Georgia Shakespeare|Georgia Shakespeare Festival]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Garner's Acting Debut|url=http://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2011/04/photos-arthur-and-ben-jennifer-garners-acting-debut|website=[[Radar Online]] |publisher=[[American Media (publisher)|American Media]]|date=April 13, 2011|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> Garner moved to New York City in 1995.<ref name="njent">{{cite web|first=Stephen |last=Whitty | url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/movies/index.ssf/2012/08/jennifer_garner_interview.html |title=Jennifer Garner interview: Still the girl next door |publisher=NJ.com |date=August 12, 2012 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> During her first year in the city, Garner earned $150 per week as an [[understudy]] for a [[Roundabout Theatre Company]] production of ''[[A Month in the Country (play)|A Month in the Country]]'', starring [[Helen Mirren]] and [[F. Murray Abraham]],<ref name=Pringle/><ref name="nymag1">{{cite web|last=Kachka |first=Boris |url=http://nymag.com/arts/theater/features/39926/ |title='Cyrano de Bergerac' Actress Jennifer Garner on Taking Her Chances on Broadway – New York Magazine |publisher=Nymag.com |date=October 28, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and made her first on-screen appearance as [[Melissa Gilbert]]'s daughter in the romance miniseries ''[[Zoya (novel)|Zoya]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor |first=John J. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/15/arts/tv-weekend-she-was-a-russian-countess-until-the-revolution.html |title=TV WEEKEND – She Was a Russian Countess, Until the Revolution |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=September 15, 1995 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 1996 she played an Amish woman in the television movie ''[[Harvest of Fire]]''<ref>{{cite web|first=Todd |last=Everett |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/hallmark-hall-of-fame-harvest-of-fire-1200445595/ |title=Hallmark Hall of Fame Harvest of Fire |publisher=Variety |date=April 19, 1996 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and a flirtatious shopkeeper in the Western miniseries ''[[Dead Man's Walk (miniseries)|Dead Man's Walk]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tony |last=Scott |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/larry-mcmurtry-s-dead-man-s-walk-1200445885/ |title=Larry Mcmurtry's 'Dead Man's Walk' |publisher=Variety |date=May 9, 1996 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> She appeared in the independent short film ''In Harm's Way''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/~krawitz/IN%20HARM%27S%20WAY/IHW.html |title=Jan Krawitz: In Harm's Way |publisher=Web.stanford.edu |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and made one-off appearances in the legal dramas ''[[Swift Justice]]'' and ''[[Law & Order]]''. She met [[Stephen Colbert]] while filming an episode of ''[[Spin City]]'' and became an occasional babysitter for his children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Garner reveals her strange connection to Stephen Colbert|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/video/tvshowbiz/video-1090425/Jennifer-Garner-reveals-strange-connection-Stephen-Colbert.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]}}</ref> Garner also supplemented her income by working as a hostess at Isabella's restaurant on the [[Upper East Side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/maxmara-party-honoring-jennifer-garner-as-new-face |title=An Event Honoring Jennifer Garner as the New Face of MaxMara Accessories |publisher=Vogue |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

After moving to Los Angeles in 1997, Garner won her first leading role in the television movie ''[[Rose Hill (film)|Rose Hill]]''<ref>{{cite web|first=Tony |last=Scott |url=https://variety.com/1997/tv/reviews/rose-hill-1200449599/amp/ |title=Rose Hill – Variety |publisher=Variety.com |date=April 18, 1997 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and made her first feature film appearance in the period drama ''[[Washington Square (film)|Washington Square]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Marlow |last=Stern |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/05/jennifer-garner-pregnant-talks-butter-and-ben-affleck-at-telluride.html |title=Jennifer Garner Pregnant, Talks 'Butter' and Ben Affleck at Telluride |publisher=The Daily Beast |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> She appeared in the comedy movie ''[[Mr. Magoo (film)|Mr. Magoo]]'', the independent drama ''1999'' and [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Deconstructing Harry]]''; most of her performance was cut from Allen's film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/jennifer-garner-actress-with-the-ex-factor-1679610.html |title=Jennifer Garner: Actress with the ex factor |publisher=The Independent |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 1998, Garner appeared in an episode of ''[[Fantasy Island (1998 TV series)|Fantasy Island]]'' and was cast as a series regular in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] drama ''[[Significant Others (1998 TV series)|Significant Others]]''. Will Joyner of ''The New York Times'' praised her ability to "provide the leavening ingredient of innocent insight"<ref>{{cite news|first=Will |last=Joyner |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/11/arts/television-review-prime-time-starting-out-in-la-at-25.html |title=Television Review; Prime Time: Starting Out In L.A. at 25 – The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=March 11, 1998 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> but Ken Tucker of ''Entertainment Weekly'' felt there was no center to the character, as played by Garner.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ken |last=Tucker |url=http://ew.com/article/1998/03/20/significant-others-party-five/ |title=Significant Others; Party of Five |publisher=Ew.com |date=March 20, 1998 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Fox cancelled the series after airing three of six filmed episodes. Garner's most significant role of 1998 was in [[J.J. Abrams]]' college drama ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]''. During a two-episode guest appearance, she befriended Abrams and met her first husband [[Scott Foley]].<ref name="usatoday2002">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/enter/tv/2002/2002-02-01-garner.htm |title=Sydney Bristow in the flesh |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=January 31, 2002 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 1999, Garner was cast as a series regular in another [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] drama, ''[[Time of Your Life (U.S. TV series)|Time of Your Life]]'', but it was cancelled midway through the first season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/zap-best-worst-tv-spinoffs-pictures-027-photo.html |title='Time of Your Life' |publisher=LA Times |date=November 16, 2013 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Also in 1999, she appeared in the miniseries ''[[Aftershock: Earthquake in New York]]'' and in two episodes of the action drama ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]''. Garner played the girlfriend of [[Ashton Kutcher]]'s character in the comedy ''[[Dude, Where's My Car?]]'' (2000). In 2001, she appeared briefly opposite her husband Foley in the drama ''[[Stealing Time]]'' and had a small role as a nurse in the war epic ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff |first=Movieline |url=http://movieline.com/2001/04/01/jennifer-garner/ |title=Jennifer Garner |publisher=Movieline |date=April 1, 2001 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

Garner rose to fame in 2001 when she was cast as the star of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] spy drama ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]''.<ref name="rollingstone1"/> The show's creator, J.J. Abrams, wrote the part of [[Sydney Bristow]] with Garner in mind: "I always thought she had something in her personality that was funnier and sexier and smarter and more mischievous than anything I'd seen her do ... I wanted to show that."<ref name="usatoday2002"/> However, he had to convince wary studio executives that Garner was right for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2004/04/23/jennifer-garner-next-julia-roberts/|title=Is Jennifer Garner the next Julia Roberts?|date=April 23, 2004|website=ew.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Robert Bianco of ''USA Today'' remarked: "You've probably never noticed her. You'll notice her now ... Garner creates one of the season's strongest new characters — a sensitive young woman who hides her vulnerability behind a mean right cross."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/enter/tv/2001-09-28-alias-review.htm |title='Alias' whips espionage into entertaining eye candy |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=September 28, 2001 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Julie Salamon of ''The New York Times'' said she brought "an attractive combination of vulnerability and entrepreneurial self-protectiveness" to the role.<ref>{{cite news|first=Julie |last=salamon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/29/arts/critic-s-notebook-two-new-spy-series-at-unexpected-risk.html |title=Critic's Notebook; Two New Spy Series at Unexpected Risk – The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=September 29, 2001 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> ''Alias'' aired for five seasons between 2001 and 2006; Garner's salary began at $40,000 per episode and rose to $150,000 per episode by the series' end.<ref>{{cite news|last=Susman|first=Gary|url=http://ew.com/article/2003/08/01/jennifer-garner-reups-alias-150k-ep/|title=Jennifer Garner reups with ''Alias'' for $150K per ep|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 1, 2003|accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> During the show's run, Garner won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Screen Actors Guild Award for Best Actress]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress – Television Series Drama|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]] (with a further three Globe nominations), and received four nominations for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Emmy Award for Best Actress]].

===2002–2011: Transition to film===
While ''Alias'' was airing, Garner continued to work in film intermittently. She had an "other-worldly" experience when [[Steven Spielberg]] called to offer her a role as a high-class call girl in ''[[Catch Me if You Can]]'' (2002).<ref name="cbr">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/electrifying-lady-garner-discusses-playing-elektra-in-daredevil/ |title=Electrifying lady: Garner discusses playing Elektra in 'Daredevil' |publisher=CBR |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> After seeing her in ''Alias'', Speilberg felt sure "she would be the next superstar".<ref>{{cite web|title=Catch Me If You Can: Production Notes|url=http://culture.com/articles/1758/catch-me-if-you-can-production-notes.phtml|publisher=Culture.com|accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref> She filmed her scene opposite [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] during a one-day shoot.<ref>{{cite web|last=Head |first=Steve |url=http://ie.ign.com/articles/2002/12/20/an-interview-with-leonardo-dicaprio |title=An Interview with Leonardo DiCaprio – IGN |publisher=Ie.ign.com |date=December 20, 2002 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Garner's first co-starring film role was in the action movie ''Daredevil'' (2003), in which she played [[Elektra Natchios|Elektra]] to [[Ben Affleck]]'s ''Daredevil''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Todd |last=McCarthy |url=https://variety.com/2003/film/reviews/daredevil-1200543427/ |title=Daredevil |publisher=Variety |date=February 13, 2003 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> The physicality required for the role was something Garner had discovered "an aptitude for" while working on ''Alias.''<ref name="cbr"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/ben-affleck-man-without-fear-part-2/ |title=Ben Affleck, Man Without Fear, Part 2 |publisher=CBR |date=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Elvis Mitchell of ''The New York Times'' said she "realizes Elektra more through movement than by way of her lumpy, obvious lines. She hasn't mastered the combat skill of tossing off bad material."<ref>{{cite news|last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9400E0D7143AF937A25751C0A9659C8B63 |title=Movie Review – Blind Lawyer As Hero In Red |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> While ''Daredevil'' received mixed reviews, it was a box office success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=daredevil.htm|title=Daredevil (2003) |accessdate=January 23, 2010|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> Also in 2003, Garner voiced herself in an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''.

Garner's first leading film role, in the romantic comedy ''[[13 Going on 30]]'' (2004), was widely praised. She played a teenager who finds herself trapped in the body of a 30-year-old. Garner chose [[Gary Winick]] to direct the film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/07/16/gary_winick_13_going_on_30_interview.shtml |title=Films – Gary Winick |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and they continued to look for other projects to do together until his death in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2011/03/remembering-gary-winick-caroline-kaplan-jennifer-garner-jason-kliot-and-more-243485/ |title=Remembering Gary Winick: Caroline Kaplan, Jennifer Garner, Jason Kliot and More |publisher=IndieWire |date=May 21, 2016 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amanda-seyfried-jennifer-garner-pay-162540 |title=Amanda Seyfried, Jennifer Garner Pay Tribute to Director Gary Winick |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Manohla Dargis of the ''Los Angeles Times'' found her "startling": "Whenever she's on screen you don't want to look anywhere else."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/apr/23/entertainment/et-dargis23 |title=Garner grows in fun '13–30' – latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=April 23, 2004 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Owen Gleiberman of ''Entertainment Weekly'' praised an "utterly beguiling" performance: "You can pinpoint the moment in it when Garner becomes a star."<ref>{{cite web|first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |url=http://ew.com/article/2004/04/22/13-going-30-2/ |title=13 Going on 30 |publisher=Ew.com |date=April 22, 2004 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Ann Hornaday of ''The Washington Post'' remarked: "Garner is clearly cut out to be America's next Sweetheart; she has the same magic mix of allure and accessibility that the job calls for."<ref>{{cite web|last=Hornaday |first=Ann |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2004/04/23/13-going-on-30-adds-up-to-fun/ee0865da-de03-4731-b4a3-ed2d0f5ecbee/ |title='13 Going on 30' Adds Up to Fun |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 23, 2004 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> ''13 Going on 30'' grossed US$96 million worldwide.<ref name="Boxofficemojo2">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=13goingon30.htm|title=13 Going on 30 (2004) |accessdate=January 23, 2010|publisher=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> Garner reprised the character of Elektra in the 2005 ''Daredevil'' spin-off ''Elektra''; it was a box office and critical failure.<ref>[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/elektra "Elektra (2005)"]. [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. Retrieved February 11, 2017.</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' concluded that Garner "is far more appealing when she's playing charming and adorable, as she did so winningly in ''13 Going on 30''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Puig |first=Claudia |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2005-01-13-elektra-review_x.htm |title='Elektra' is a fight to the finish |website=USA Today |date=January 13, 2005 |accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> Garner next starred opposite [[Timothy Olyphant]] in the romantic drama ''[[Catch and Release (film)|Catch and Release]]''. Although filmed in 2005 in between seasons of ''Alias'', it was not released until early 2007 and failed to recoup its production budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=catchandrelease.htm |title=Catch and Release (2007) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Peter Travers of ''Rolling Stone'' praised Garner's ability "to blend charm and gravity"<ref>{{cite web|last=Travers |first=Peter |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/catch-and-release-20070124 |title=Catch and Release |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=January 24, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> but Peter Hartlaub of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' felt that, while her "natural beauty and likability are still assets, [she] seems occasionally challenged by what should be an easy role."<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartlaub |first=Peter |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/About-that-dead-fiance-of-yours-2621400.php |title=About that dead fiance of yours ... |publisher=SFGate |date=January 26, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

After a one-year break following the conclusion of ''Alias'', her wedding to Affleck, and the birth of her first child, Garner returned to work in 2007. Her supporting role in ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' as a woman desperate to adopt a child was described by Kyle Buchanan of ''New York Magazine'' as a turning point in her career: "She came into the movie a steely figure, and left it as the mother you'd give your own child to ... Writer [[Diablo Cody]] and director [[Jason Reitman]] expertly deploy Garner's innate humanity as a trump card."<ref>{{cite web|last=Buchanan |first=Kyle|url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/04/jennifer-garners-best-movie-scene-is-in-juno.html|title=When Did Jennifer Garner Switch From Ass-Kicker to Maternal Figure?|date=April 11, 2014|publisher=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]}}</ref> Lisa Schwarzbaum of ''Entertainment Weekly'' said she had never "been lovelier or more affecting."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2008/01/09/juno|title=Juno|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 9, 2008|last=Schwarzbuam |first=Lisa}}</ref> She played an FBI investigator in the action thriller ''[[The Kingdom (film)|The Kingdom]]'' (2007).<ref>{{cite web|last=Puig |first=Claudia |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-09-27-kingdom_N.htm |title=Action aces cohesion in 'The Kingdom' - USATODAY.com |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=September 28, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Mick |last=LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Review-of-The-Kingdom-Hunt-for-terrorists-2500597.php |title=Review of 'The Kingdom': Hunt for terrorists abroad proves not so easy |publisher=SFGate |date=September 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> She was nursing her baby during filming in Arizona and was hospitalized on two occasions with heatstroke.<ref name="radiofree1">{{cite web|url=http://movies.radiofree.com/interviews/thekingd_jennifer_garner.shtml |title=RadioFree.com &#124; Jennifer Garner Interviews, The Kingdom |publisher=Movies.radiofree.com |date=August 24, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> In late 2007 and early 2008 Garner played Roxanne to [[Kevin Kline]]'s ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' at the [[Richard Rodgers Theatre]] on Broadway. In preparation for the role, Garner worked with vocal and movement coaches and took French lessons.<ref name="nymag1"/> Ben Brantley of ''The New York Times'' described her performance as "captivating": " Ms. Garner, I am pleased to report, makes Roxane a girl worth pining over ... [She] speaks Anthony Burgess's peppery rhymed translation with unaffected sprightliness. If she's a tad stilted in the big tragic finale, her comic timing is impeccable."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/02/theater/reviews/02cyra.html |title=Rapier Wit and a Nose for Poetry|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 2, 2007 |first=Ben |last=Brantley |accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> ''The New Yorker''{{'}}s theater critic was impressed by her "feistiness" and " lightness of comic touch".<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayer |first=Jane |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/11/12/fighting-and-writing |title=Fighting and Writing |publisher=The New Yorker |date=March 27, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> The play was [[Cyrano de Bergerac (2008 film)|recorded]] before a live audience and aired on [[PBS]] in 2008. In 2007, Garner became a spokesperson of skin care brand [[Neutrogena]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=De Leon|first1=Kris|title=Jennifer Garner To Represent Neutrogena |url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/alias/jennifer-garner-to-represent-n-7695.aspx|website=[[BuddyTV]]|accessdate=August 18, 2014|date=June 26, 2007}}</ref>

[[File:Jennifer Garner cropped.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Garner at a press conference for ''[[The Invention of Lying]]'' in 2009]]

Garner co-starred in two romantic comedies in 2009. She first appeared opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]] in ''[[Ghosts of Girlfriends Past]]'', portraying the childhood friend of a famous photographer and womanizer (McConaughey). While the film received lukewarm reviews, it grossed US$102.2 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostsofgirlfriendspast.htm|title=Ghosts of Girlfriends Past (2009) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Michael Phillips of ''The Chicago Tribune'' found Garner "easy to like and sharp with her timing", he was disappointed to see her as "the love interest, which is not the same as a rounded character."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/talking_pictures/2009/04/ghosts-of-girlfriends-past---2-12-stars.html |title=Talking Pictures: 'Ghosts of Girlfriends Past' −2 1/2 stars |publisher=Featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com |date=April 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Similarly, Manohla Dargis of ''The New York Times'' was dismayed to see the actress appear as "less a co-star than a place holder (you can almost see the words "enter generic female lead" in [the] screenplay)."<ref>{{cite news|first=Manohla |last=Dargis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/01/movies/01ghos.html |title=Matthew McConaughey as a Cad Who Loved Too Often but Not Wisely – The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=April 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

Garner's second performance of 2009 was opposite comedian [[Ricky Gervais]] in his directorial debut ''[[The Invention of Lying]]''. Gervais was keen to cast Garner – "always happy and always pleasant to everyone" – against type.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2009/09/23/gervais-on-goody-two-shoes-garner-437896/ |title=Gervais on 'Goody Two Shoes' Garner &#124; Metro News |publisher=Metro.co.uk |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In the film, she played the love interest of the first human with the ability to lie (Gervais) in a world where people can only tell the truth. Reviews for the movie were mixed and it made US$32.4 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inventionoflying.htm |title=The Invention of Lying (2009) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> David Edelstein of ''New York Magazine'' said she "proves again (the first time was ''13 Going on 30'') what a dizzying comedienne she is. She looks as if the wheels in her head are not just turning but falling off and needing to be screwed back on."<ref>{{cite web|last=Edelstein |first=David |url=http://nymag.com/movies/reviews/59250/ |title=The Invention of Lying – Brief Interviews With Hideous Men – Coco Before Chanel – New York Magazine Movie Review |publisher=Nymag.com |date=September 20, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> while Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said she "has never been better onscreen [...] Garner gets to show a comic facility we haven't seen before."<ref>{{cite web|first=Mick |last=LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Review-The-Invention-of-Lying-3285398.php |title=Review: 'The Invention of Lying' |publisher=SFGate |date=October 2, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

In [[Garry Marshall]]'s ensemble romantic comedy ''[[Valentine's Day (2010 film)|Valentine's Day]]'' (2010), she shared scenes with Ashton Kutcher, [[Jessica Biel]] and [[Patrick Dempsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=valentinesday.htm|title=Valentine's Day (2010)|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=January 8, 2013}}</ref> The film made US$56.2 million in its U.S. opening weekend,; it eventually grossed US$110.4 million domestically and US$216.4 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=valentinesday.htm |title=Valentine's Day (2010) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> In 2011, she had a supporting role as a villainous arranged bride in the comedy ''[[Arthur (2011 film)|Arthur]]'', a remake of the 1981 [[Arthur (1981 film)|film of the same name]], directed by [[Steve Gordon (director)|Steve Gordon]] and co-starring [[Russell Brand]] and [[Helen Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sharkey |first=Betsy |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/08/entertainment/la-et-arthur-20110408 |title='Arthur': Movie review – latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Justin |last=Chang |url=https://variety.com/2011/film/reviews/arthur-1117944968/ |title=Arthur |publisher=Variety |date=April 4, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

===2012–present===
[[File:Jennifer Garner Butter premiere 2011 Toronto FIlm Festival (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Garner at the premiere of ''[[Butter (2011 film)|Butter]]'' in 2011]]

Garner played a mother for the first time in 2012,<ref name="telegraph2"/> starring opposite [[Joel Edgerton]], in the drama ''[[The Odd Life of Timothy Green]]'', which followed a magical pre-adolescent boy whose personality and naïveté have profound effects on the people in his town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/the-odd-life-timothy-green-trailer/|title='The Odd Life of Timothy Green' Trailer: Who's That Kid?|website=[[/Film]]|date=August 8, 2011 |last=Fischer |first=Russ}}</ref> The film  received mixed reviews from critics and made a modest US$56 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_odd_life_of_timothy_green |title=The Odd Life of Timothy Green (2012)|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oddlifeoftimothygreen.htm|title=The Odd Life of Timothy Green|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''USA Today'' found her "convincing as a warm-hearted, if tense, mom"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/story/2012-08-16/the-odd-life-of-timothy-green-jennifer-garner/57075654/1|title=Big ideas fail to sprout in well-meaning 'Timothy Green'|website=usatoday.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> while Michael Phillips of the ''Chicago Tribune'' said she brought "fervent sincerity and a welcome touch of comic eccentricity" to the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-0813-odd-life-timothy-green-20120815-column.html|title='Odd Life of Timothy Green' a tale of a little green sprout ★★ 1/2|first=Michael|last=Phillips |website=chicagotribune.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2012, Garner starred in the satirical comedy ''[[Butter (2011 film)|Butter]]'', in which she played an overly competitive and socially ambitious woman participating in a local [[butter sculpture|butter sculpturing]] competition in a small [[Iowa]] town. Distributed for a limited release in certain parts of the United States only, ''Butter'' received mixed reviews and grossed US$105,018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/butter_2011/|title=Butter (2012)|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=butter.htm|title=Butter|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=February 11, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''Variety'' praised "the best bigscreen use of Jennifer Garner's comedy gifts since ''13 Going on 30''"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2011/film/reviews/butter-1117945969/|title=Butter|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| first=Peter|last=Debruge |date=September 5, 2011}}</ref> while Peter Travers of ''Rolling Stone'' described her as the "best in show" : "[She] knows how to play comedy of the absurd."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/butter-20121004|title=Butter |website=rollingstone.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> However, Scott Bowles of ''USA Today'' remarked: "Garner is a terrific actress, but here she's asked to cackle her lines in a voice a full octave above her natural one."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2012/10/04/butter-movie-review/1612501/|title='Butter': A recipe for stale laughs |website=usatoday.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2012, she appeared opposite [[Alfred Molina]] in the YouTube short ''Serena'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/jennifer-garner-wigs-serena-alfred-molina-327801 |title=Jennifer Garner Confesses Her Twisted Fantasies in New YouTube Short (Video) |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter |date=May 22, 2012 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> and became a spokesperson for food company Luvo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lululemon's Day to Lead Derek Jeter-Backed Food Maker|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-01-14/lululemon-s-day-to-lead-derek-jeter-backed-food-maker.html|newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]]|accessdate=August 30, 2014 |first=Leslie|last=Patton|date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>

Garner reunited with [[Matthew McConaughey]] in the 2013 drama ''[[Dallas Buyers Club]]'', portraying the role of a doctor treating [[AIDS]] patients in Texas during the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dallas_buyers_club_2013/|title=Dallas Buyers Club (2013)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Flixster]]|accessdate=January 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dallasbuyersclub.htm|title=Dallas Buyers Club|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> The film received significant acclaim and was a box office success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dallasbuyersclub.htm|title=Dallas Buyers Club (2013) - Box Office Mojo |website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Peter Travers of ''Rolling Stone'' described her as "a radiant actress of rare spirit and sensitivity"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/dallas-buyers-club-20131031|title=Dallas Buyers Club|website=rollingstone.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> and Betsy Sharkey of the ''Los Angeles Times'' said: "Garner is once again cast as a quintessentially decent, all-American girl, albeit a doctor. But the question of whether the actress has deeper emotional layers to bring to the screen is not answered here."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-dallas-buyers-club-review-story.html#axzz2jEyeTTsa|title=Review: 'Dallas Buyers Club' led well by McConaughey, Leto|date=October 31, 2013|website=Latimes.com |accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> David Edelstein of ''New York Magazine'' said: "It's not a well-shaped role, but I've gotten to the point where I'm happy to see Garner in anything. She's incapable of phoniness."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/movies/reviews/dallas-buyers-club-about-time-2013-11/|title=Outlaw Pharmacology|website=nymag.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2013, Garner became the first celebrity spokesperson of the Italian fashion brand [[Max Mara]].<ref name="USA Today 2013">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2013/07/16/jennifer-garner-is-the-new-face-of-max-mara/2521359/ | title=Jennifer Garner is the new face of Max Mara |newspaper=USA Today | date=July 16, 2013 | accessdate=July 17, 2013 | first=Maria |last=Puente}}</ref>

In 2014, Garner starred opposite [[Kevin Costner]] in the sports drama ''[[Draft Day]]'', as the fictional salary cap analyst of [[Cleveland Browns]]. Critical reception towards the film was mixed and  Mick LaSalle of ''The San Francisco Chronicle'' describing her part, remarked: "It's not much of a role, but she's perfectly nice in it. Perhaps someday someone will give Garner a chance to be something other than perfectly nice."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Draft-Day-review-Kevin-Costner-makes-big-plays-5393547.php|title='Draft Day' review: Kevin Costner makes big plays|website=sfgate.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Garner also co-starred with [[Steve Carell]] in the 2014 Disney [[Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day (film)|adaptation]] of the popular children's book ''[[Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day]]'', taking on the role of the mother of the titular character. The film grossed US$101 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=alexanderbadday.htm|title=Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day (2014) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Sandie Angulo Chen of the ''Washington Post'' said: "Garner, who has long mastered the art of playing harried and overworked moms, is pleasantly frazzled."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/alexander-and-the-terrible-horrible-no-good-very-bad-day-movie-review-a-comedic-romp-that-everyone-can-enjoy/2014/10/09/c6313ecc-4e69-11e4-aa5e-7153e466a02d_story.html |title='Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day' movie review: A comedic romp that everyone can enjoy|first1=Sandie Angulo|last1=Chen|first2=Sandie Angulo|last2=Chen |date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=April 19, 2017|website=Washingtonpost.com}}</ref> Her other film role in 2014 was that of an overprotective mother in the dramedy ''[[Men, Women & Children (film)|Men, Women & Children]]'', directed by [[Jason Reitman]] and co-starring [[Rosemarie DeWitt]], [[Judy Greer]], [[Dean Norris]], and [[Adam Sandler]]. The film made a US$2.2 million worldwide,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=menwomenandchildren.htm |title=Men, Women & Children (2014) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> and Christopher Orr of ''The Atlantic'' said: "Garner does what she can as the Snooping Mom from Hell, but ultimately it's not much. The role is like a caricature of her performance in ''Juno'', minus the ultimate (and essential) redemption."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/10/men-women-children-the-anti-juno/381296/|title=Men, Women & Children: The Anti-Juno|first=Christopher|last=Orr |website=theatlantic.com|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> In late 2014, [[Capital One]] signed Garner as their spokeswoman for their Capital One Venture Air Miles credit card.<ref>Kiefaber, David (September 16, 2014). [http://www.adweek.com/creativity/jennifer-garner-returns-tv-capital-ones-newest-spokes-celebrity-160155/ "Jennifer Garner Returns to TV as Capital One's Newest Spokes-Celebrity"]. ''[[Adweek]]''.</ref>

In 2015's ''[[Danny Collins (film)|Danny Collins]]'', a drama inspired by the true story of folk singer [[Steve Tilston]] and starring [[Al Pacino]] and [[Annette Bening]], Garner played the supporting role of the wife of [[Bobby Cannavale]]'s character. The film was released in selected cinemas and was warmly received by critics; Stephanie Merry of the ''Washington Post'' felt she "gives the movie a powerful jolt of emotion."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/al-pacino-charms-as-an-aging-soul-searching-rocker-in-danny-collins/2015/03/25/987c9d32-ce4d-11e4-a2a7-9517a3a70506_story.html|title=Al Pacino charms as an aging, soul-searching rocker in 'Danny Collins'|first1=Stephanie|last1=Merry |first2=Stephanie|last2=Merry |date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=April 19, 2017|website=Washingtonpost.com}}</ref> In 2016, Garner appeared in the Christian drama ''[[Miracles from Heaven (film)|Miracles from Heaven]]'', playing the mother of a young girl who had a near-death experience and was later cured of an incurable disease. The film grossed US$73.9 million worldwide<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=miraclesfromheaven.htm|title=Miracles from Heaven (2016) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> and received generally mixed reviews from critics, who felt it "makes the most out of an outstanding performance"  from Garner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/miracles_from_heaven/ |title=Miracles from Heaven|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref> Ken Jaworowski of ''The New York Times'' praised a "dedicated" and "heartfelt" performance<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/16/movies/review-miracles-from-heaven-starring-jennifer-garner-as-the-mother-of-a-sick-child.html|title=Review: 'Miracles From Heaven,' Starring Jennifer Garner as the Mother of a Sick Child|first=Ken|last=Jaworowski |date=March 15, 2016|accessdate=April 19, 2017|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> while Nigel Smith of ''The Guardian'' found "her subtly wrought work [...] tremendously effective" in an otherwise "crassly manipulative" film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/mar/18/miracles-from-heaven-review-jennifer-garner|title=Miracles From Heaven review: Jennifer Garner overcomes preachy drama|first=Nigel M.|last=Smith|date=March 18, 2016|accessdate=April 19, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Also in 2016, she starred opposite [[Kevin Spacey]] in the critically panned comedy ''[[Nine Lives (2016 film)|Nine Lives]]'', playing the second wife of a workaholic father who has his mind trapped inside of his daughter's new cat. Garner made an uncredited cameo appearance in ''[[Mother's Day (2016 film)|Mother's Day]]'' (2016).

Garner appeared in the drama ''[[Wakefield (film)|Wakefield]]'', which premiered at TIFF and was released in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hipes |first=Patrick |url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/wakefield-release-date-bryan-cranston-jennifer-garner-ifc-films-1202050177/ |title='Wakefield' Movie Acquired By IFC Films For May Release |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 23, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2017, she starred in ''[[The Tribes of Palos Verdes]]'', and in friend [[Judy Greer]]'s directorial debut ''[[A Happening of Monumental Proportions]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tv3.ie/xpose/article/entertainment-news/235013/Judy-Greer-auditioned-parents-to-land-cool-child-stars-for-new-movie |title=Judy Greer auditioned parents to land cool child stars for new movie – TV3 Xposé |publisher=Tv3.ie |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charitybuzz.com/catalog_items/lunch-with-judy-greer-in-los-angeles-1215200 |title=Lunch with Judy Greer in Los Angeles – Lot 1215200 |publisher=Charitybuzz |date=January 5, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, she co-starred in ''[[Love, Simon]]'', an adaptation of the young adult novel ''[[Simon vs. the Homo Sapiens Agenda]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave |last=McNary |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/jennifer-garner-nick-robinson-simon-vs-the-homo-sapiens-agenda-1201993378/ |title=Jennifer Garner Joins Nick Robinson's 'Simon Vs. The Homo Sapiens' |publisher=Variety |date=February 21, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Also that year, Garner voiced the role of Mama Llama for Netflix's original animated preschool series ''[[Llama Llama]]'', and starred as the lead in the action-revenge film ''[[Peppermint (2018 film)|Peppermint]]'', which was released on September 7.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/jennifer-garner-peppermint-stx-movie-release-date-1202351532/ |title=Jennifer Garner Thriller 'Peppermint' Sets Post-Labor Day Weekend Debut |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 22, 2018 |accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, she was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/celebrity/jennifer-garner-is-surrounded-by-family-including-her-3-kids-at-her-hollywood-star-ceremony/ss-BBMbF60|title=Jennifer Garner Is Surrounded by Family - Including Her 3 Kids! - at Her Hollywood Star Ceremony|website=www.msn.com |language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>

==Activism==
===Early childhood education===
[[File:Early Learning Bill.jpg|thumb|Garner with a preschooler at a [[Capitol Hill]] event in 2013]]
In 2009, Garner became an artist ambassador for [[Save the Children]], promoting national literacy, nutrition and early education efforts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Freydkin |first=Donna |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2009-05-01-garner-instyle_N.htm |title=Garner: 'As frazzled as any working mother' - USATODAY.com |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=May 1, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8lKp2rZdTw|title=Jennifer Garner Lends a Hand|first=|last=CBS|date=April 30, 2010|accessdate=April 19, 2017|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Since 2014,<ref>{{cite press release |last=Grozdanic |first=Ajla |date=March 18, 2014 |title=Jennifer Garner Joins Save the Children's Board of Trustees |url=http://www.savethechildren.org/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=8rKLIXMGIpI4E&b=8943305&ct=13746733&notoc=1 |location=[[Westport, Connecticut]]|publisher=Save the Children |access-date=January 6, 2016}}</ref> Garner has served on the board of trustees for the organization,<ref name=VanityFair>Smith, Krista (February 26, 2016). [http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/02/jennifer-garner-talks-kids-career-ben-affleck "Exclusive: Jennifer Garner's Frank Talk About Kids, Men, and Ben Affleck"]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.</ref><ref name=Forbes>Mendelson, Scott (July 1, 2015). [https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/07/01/ben-afflecks-career-survived-daredevil-but-jennifer-garner-never-recovered-from-elektra/ "Ben Affleck Survived 'Daredevil,' But Jennifer Garner Never Recovered From 'Elektra'"]. ''[[Forbes]]''.</ref><ref>Jordan, Julie (April 14, 2014). "Jennifer Garner: She helps moms bond with their kids over books". ''People'', p. 42.</ref> advocating for early childhood education.<ref>{{cite web|title=Save the Children Artist Ambassador Jennifer Garner Joins Capitol Hill Push to Expand Early Education in America|last=Weinberg |first=Tanya|url=http://www.savethechildren.org/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=8rKLIXMGIpI4E&b=8486803&ct=13392075|publisher=[[Save the Children]]|date=November 13, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> As an ambassador she frequently visits with families involved in the organization's Early Steps to School Success program, which coaches families to help children learn in the early years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/celebrity/jennifer-garner-joins-save-the-childrens-board-of-trustees/|title=Jennifer Garner Joins Save the Children's Board of Trustees|date=March 14, 2014|newspaper=People|last=Leon |first=Anya}}</ref>

In 2011, Garner partnered with [[Frigidaire]] as part of her work with Save The Children.<ref>Turner, Lauren (September 21, 2011). [http://www.popsugar.com/celebrity/Jennifer-Garner-Pregnant-Frigidaire-Event-Pictures-19166194#photo-19166194 "Jennifer Garner Cooks Up a Cute Pregnant Appearance"]. [[PopSugar]].</ref> In 2013, Garner took her eldest daughter Violet to a Save The Children gala in New York: "My husband and I have never taken our kids to a public event before, but I brought my daughter Violet, because ... I want her to see the passionate commitment [[Mark Shriver]] and [[Hillary Clinton]] have to make the world a better place for everyone."<ref>{{cite web|last=Marcus |first=Bennett|title=Jennifer Garner Refers to Hillary Clinton as 'Our Next President,' Brings Her Daughter Violet Out for Her First Public Event |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2013/10/jennifer-garner-hillary-clinton-president-violet_slideshow_item9_10|newspaper=Vanity Fair|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, she joined the Invest in Us campaign.<ref name=Forbes/> In 2015, she appeared in ''A Path Appears'', a PBS documentary which focuses on rural poverty among children in West Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://features.aol.com/video/new-pbs-series-examines-lives-american-children-growing-poverty|title=New PBS series examines the lives of American children growing up in poverty |publisher=[[AOL]]|date=January 2015|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref>

===Other===
In 2002, Garner filmed a 30-second television advertisement for her childhood friend [[Corey Palumbo]], running as a Democratic candidate for the [[West Virginia House of Delegates]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Marks|first=Rusty|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-13806435.html |title=Garnering recognition: Candidate enlists 'Alias' star for political ad |publisher=The Charleston Gazette |date=October 18, 2002 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> In 2006, she spoke at a rally in support of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Congressional candidate [[Jerry McNerney]] in [[Pleasanton, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Garner helps build support for McNerney|url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/argus/localnews/ci_4607118|newspaper=[[East Bay Times]]|last=Becker |first=Andrew|date=November 5, 2006}}</ref> In 2008 she hosted two fundraisers for Obama during the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2008|2008 Democratic Primary]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2008/03/17/affleck_garner_create_their_own_political_party/|title=Affleck, Garner create their own political party|website=Boston.com|accessdate=October 8, 2014|first1=Carol|last1=Beggy|first2=Mark|last2=Shanahan|date=March 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20216659,00.html|title=The Afflecks & Damons: Baby Bumps for Obama|website=PEOPLE.com|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, Garner said she was "not a particularly outwardly political person."<ref name="radiofree1"/> In 2014, Garner donated $25,000 to the campaign of Democratic politician [[Wendy Davis (politician)|Wendy Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wendy Davis' famous donors|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/gallery/Wendy-Davis-famous-donors-90077.php|date=July 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> During the 2016 presidential campaign, Garner hosted a fundraiser in support of Hillary Clinton in [[Bozeman, Montana]].<ref>Carter, Troy (August 17, 2016). [http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/blogs/politics/actress-jennifer-garner-in-bozeman-to-pool-cash-for-candidate/article_939aa953-cd00-587f-856f-898e1abfbdf5.html "Actress Jennifer Garner in Bozeman to pool cash for candidate"]. 406 Politics, ''[[Bozeman Daily Chronicle]]'' ([[Bozeman, Montana]]).</ref> Garner also attended voter registration and phone bank events in support of Clinton in [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref>[http://mynews4.com/news/local/jennifer-garner-campaigns-for-hillary-clinton-in-reno "Jennifer Garner Campaigns for Hillary Clinton"]. [[KRNV-DT]] ([[Reno, Nevada]]). October 10, 2016</ref>

In 2007, Garner appeared in a global warming awareness video produced by the [[Center for American Progress Action Fund]].<ref>Stockton, Paysha. (July 23, 2007) [http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20047730,00.html VIDEO: Ben Affleck Stars in 'Corny' Environmental Ad – Ben Affleck, Matt Damon]. People.com. Retrieved on June 5, 2014.</ref>

Garner has campaigned for laws to protect her children from paparazzi. "There's an idea that because our pictures are everywhere that we are complicit in it. When really what happens is they're waiting outside our door every single day. My kids take karate for example, and we have our classes at the same time every week. So the guys know when we have karate, and so 20 of them wait there for us every single class. So that's a lot of energy coming at little, little kids."<ref>{{cite web|last=Hines |first=Ree|title=Jennifer Garner didn't believe law to protect kids from paparazzi would pass|url=http://www.today.com/entertainment/jennifer-garner-i-didnt-believe-law-protect-kids-paparazzi-would-8C11319973|website=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, Garner testified alongside [[Halle Berry]] before the California Assembly Judiciary Committee in support of a bill that would protect celebrities' children from harassment by photographers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Child|first=Ben|title=Jennifer Garner joins Halle Berry's fight for new anti-paparazzi law in California|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/aug/15/jennifer-garner-halle-berry-paparazzi-law|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 24, 2013|date=August 15, 2013}}</ref> The bill passed in September 2013 and is now California law.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|title=Anti-paparazzi bill backed by Halle Berry now California law|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/26/halle-berry-anti-paparazzi-law|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 24, 2014|date=September 26, 2013}}</ref>

== Personal life ==

=== Relationships and family ===
Garner met co-star [[Scott Foley]] on the set of ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'' in 1998.<ref name="rollingstone1"/> They married in a ceremony at their home on October 19, 2000. The couple separated in March 2003.<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephen M. |last=Silverman |url=http://people.com/celebrity/garner-she-and-foley-were-just-normal/ |title=Garner: She and Foley Were 'Just Normal' |publisher=People.com |date=October 21, 2003 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Garner filed for divorce in May 2003, citing [[irreconcilable differences]], and divorce papers were signed in March 2004.<ref>{{cite web|first=Emily |last=Zauzmer |url=http://people.com/celebrity/jennifer-garner-ben-affleck-split-a-look-back-at-her-romantic-relationships/ |title=Jennifer Garner & Ben Affleck Split: A Look Back at Her Romantic Relationships |publisher=People.com |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jennifer-garner-80d8hv50bkm |title=Jennifer Garner &#124; The Times & The Sunday Times |publisher=Thetimes.co.uk |date=August 8, 2004 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> She dated her ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' co-star [[Michael Vartan]] from August 2003 to mid-2004.<ref>{{cite web|last=Keck |first=William |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2004-09-01-alias_x.htm |title=USATODAY.com – Garnering attention |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=September 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Keck |first=William |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-05-12-vartan_x.htm |title=USATODAY.com – Stay tuned for more Michael Vartan |publisher=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=May 12, 2005 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Goldenglobes2013.png|thumb|Garner, with [[Ben Affleck]], at the [[70th Golden Globe Awards]] on January 13, 2013]]

Garner began dating [[Ben Affleck]] in mid-2004,<ref name="people5">[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1051815,00.html Ben Affleck and Jennifer Garner Engaged – Marriage, Ben Affleck, Jennifer Garner]. People.com (April 19, 2005). Retrieved on June 5, 2014.</ref> having established a friendship on the sets of ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' (2001) and ''[[Daredevil (film)|Daredevil]]'' (2003).<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20145517,00.html Scoop – Ben Affleck]. People.com. Retrieved on June 5, 2014.</ref> They were married on June 29, 2005, in a private [[Turks and Caicos Islands|Turks and Caicos]] ceremony.<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1080007_3,00.html Under the Radar – Page 3 – Marriage, Ben Affleck, Jennifer Garner]. People.com. Retrieved on June 5, 2014.</ref> [[Victor Garber]], who officiated the ceremony, and his husband Rainer Andreesen were the only guests.<ref>Garber on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' September 27, 2006, via {{cite news| url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/garber-ordained-to-officiate-garner-and-affleck-wedding_1009479 | title=Garber Ordained To Officiate Garner And Affleck Wedding| publisher= ContactMusic.com |agency= [[World Entertainment News Network]]| date= September 28, 2006| accessdate= June 5, 2014 | archivedate= March 31, 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331012241/http://www.contactmusic.com/news/garber-ordained-to-officiate-garner-and-affleck-wedding_1009479| deadurl=no}}</ref> Garner and Affleck have three children together: two daughters<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,26334,1139179,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223556/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C26334%2C1139179%2C00.html |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |title=Ben & Jen's Baby Violet Settles In |date=December 8, 2005 |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=March 17, 2017 |deadurl=yes |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20252295,00.html|title=Jennifer Garner and Ben Affleck Reveal Baby's Name |last=Jordan|first=Julie |date=January 13, 2009|website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=October 26, 2011}}</ref> and one son.<ref name="son">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20560766,00.html|title=Jennifer Garner and Ben Affleck Welcome Third Child|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref> The couple announced their intention to divorce in June 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/ben-affleck-jennifer-garner-split|title=Ben Affleck and Jennifer Garner Divorcing After 10 Years of Marriage|website=People|first1=Michelle|last1=Tauber |first2=Elizabeth|last2=Leonard|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> and jointly filed legal documents in April 2017, seeking joint physical and legal custody of their children.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Russian|first1=Ale|title=Jennifer Garner Officially Files for Divorce from Ben Affleck|url=http://people.com/celebrity/jennifer-garner-ben-affleck-divorce/|website=People Magazine|accessdate=April 13, 2017|date=April 13, 2017}}</ref> The divorce was finalized in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/jennifer-garner-files-to-finalize-ben-affleck-divorce-report/|title=Jennifer Garner Files to Finalize Her Divorce From Ben Affleck|work=[[Us Weekly]]|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/a23622544/ben-affleck-jennifer-garner-finalize-divorce/|title=Ben Affleck and Jennifer Garner Finalize Their Divorce|last=Barbour|first=Shannon|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2018}}</ref>

===Religion===
Although Garner stopped attending church regularly after moving to Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|last=Atlas |first=Darla |url=http://www.people.com/article/jennifer-garner-opens-up-faith-family-following-premiere-miracles-heaven|title=Jennifer Garner Talks Faith and Family After Miracles from Heaven Premiere|date=February 22, 2016|newspaper=People}}</ref> each of her three children was baptized as a member of the United Methodist Church in her hometown of [[Charleston, West Virginia]].<ref name="nationalpost1">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/movies/miracles-from-heavens-jennifer-garner-on-her-emotional-role-in-miracles-from-heaven-and-keeping-it-professional|title=Jennifer Garner on her latest emotional role and keeping it professional as a mom, on and offscreen|publisher=}}</ref> In 2015, she and her family began attending weekly Methodist church services in Los Angeles.<ref name="nationalpost1"/>

===Stalking incident===
Garner was [[stalking|stalked]] by Steven Burky from 2002 to 2003, and again from 2008 to 2009. She, her husband, and her daughter Violet obtained a restraining order in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7741505.stm |title=Entertainment &#124; Garner 'feared for family safety' |publisher=BBC News |date=November 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Burky was arrested in December 2009 outside her daughter's preschool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8596274.stm|title=Jennifer Garner 'stalker' sent to mental hospital|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=February 12, 2017|date=March 31, 2010}}</ref> He was charged with two counts of stalking, to which he pleaded [[Insanity defense|not guilty by reason of insanity]]. In March 2010, he was ruled insane, sent to California's state mental hospital, and ordered to stay away from the Affleck family for 10 years if released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/celebrity/NATL-Judge-Finds-Accused-Ben-Affleck-Stalker-Insane-89554822.html|title=Judge Finds Accused Ben Affleck, Jennifer Garner Stalker Insane|first=Caitlin|last=Millat|publisher=[[WRC-TV]]/NBC4|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|date=March 30, 2010}}</ref>

